    <h1>VPAT / Accessibility Compliance Documentation</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-WhatisaVPAT?"><=
span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"f9ffdb50-5e9a-4cb4-b014-a7=
6a2b799f59">What is a VPAT?</span>&nbsp;</h2>
<p>An Accessibility Conformance Report is based on the voluntary product ac=
cessibility template (VPAT).&nbsp; The <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"h=
ttps://www.itic.org/policy/accessibility/vpat" rel=3D"nofollow">VPAT report=
 form</a> is owned by the Information Technology Industry Council (ITI) and=
 includes conformance documentation options for&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://www.federalregister.gov/docu=
ments/2018/01/22/2018-00848/information-and-communication-technology-ict-st=
andards-and-guidelines." rel=3D"nofollow">Revised Section 508 standards</a>=
&nbsp;=E2=80=93 the U.S. Federal accessibility standard</li>
<li><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"http://www.etsi.org/deliver/etsi_en/=
301500_301599/301549/01.01.02_60/en_301549v010102p.pdf" rel=3D"nofollow">EN=
 301 549</a>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 the European Union=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CAccessibi=
lity requirements suitable for public procurement of ICT products and servi=
ces in Europe=E2=80=9D</li>
<li><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/2008/REC-WCAG2=
0-20081211/" rel=3D"nofollow">WCAG 2.0</a>&nbsp;or ISO/IEC 40500 =E2=80=93 =
W3C/WAI=E2=80=99s Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</li>
</ul>
<p>The VPAT is a living report form and will be regularly updated by the IT=
I to reflect changes to conformance standards (e.g. update from WCAG 2.0 to=
 WCAG 2.1).</p>
<p>Be sure to validate that you are referencing the latest <a class=3D"exte=
rnal-link" href=3D"https://www.itic.org/policy/accessibility/vpat" rel=3D"n=
ofollow">VPAT report form</a> template to understand current requirements.&=
nbsp;</p>
<h3 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-WhousesVPATs?"><span cl=
ass=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"bdc34100-0485-4bcb-bb52-3b7d52280=
e8f">Who uses VPATs?</span></h3>
<p>VPATs are often requested or required as part of the evaluation and proc=
urement process for school districts and universities.&nbsp; It helps admin=
istrators understand the accessibility levels of a product, and most import=
antly, identify any gaps that they should be aware of so that they can bett=
er support their students.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-MHE'sAccessibilityConfo=
rmanceReports">MHE's Accessibility Conformance Reports</h2>
<h3 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-RequiredReportFeatures"=
>Required Report Features</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Report Title:</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong>=E2=80=9CMcGraw-Hi=
ll Education Accessibility Conformance Report=E2=80=9D</li>
<li><strong>VPAT Heading </strong><strong>Information:</strong><strong>&nbs=
p;</strong>Template version "VPAT=C2=AE Version 2.1 =E2=80=93 March 2018"</=
li>
<li><strong>Name of Product &amp; Version:&nbsp;</strong>The customer-facin=
g application name (needs to be discernible for potential customers who are=
 evaluating the product)</li>
<li><strong>Product Description:&nbsp;</strong>Customer-facing description =
of the app's purpose; needs to be discernible for customers who are evaluat=
ing the product&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Date:</strong> VPATs report compliance at the time of testing.&=
nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Contact Information:</strong> so that people can ask further cl=
arification as needed.&nbsp;We use&nbsp;<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"=
mailto:accessibility@mheducation.com" rel=3D"nofollow">accessibility@mheduc=
ation.com</a>&nbsp;which goest to CXG.&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Evaluation Methods Used:&nbsp;</strong>This explains the scope =
of content evaluated, assistive technologies, and testing methodologies.&nb=
sp;
<ul>
<li>MHE standard ATs for VPAT:&nbsp; JAWS2018, Zoom Text, Dragon Naturally =
Speaking&nbsp;</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Applicable Standards/Guidelines:&nbsp;</strong><br>
<ul>
<li>The list must include only the Standards/Guidelines that were used to d=
evelop the product.</li>
<li>A report must contain a minimum of one Standard/Guideline or any combin=
ation of the three Standards.<br>
<ul>
<li><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://www.federalregister.gov/docu=
ments/2018/01/22/2018-00848/information-and-communication-technology-ict-st=
andards-and-guidelines." rel=3D"nofollow">Revised Section 508 standards</a>=
&nbsp;=E2=80=93 the U.S. Federal accessibility standard</li>
<li><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/2008/REC-WCAG2=
0-20081211/" rel=3D"nofollow">WCAG 2.0</a>&nbsp;or ISO/IEC 40500 =E2=80=93 =
W3C/WAI=E2=80=99s Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Terms:&nbsp;</strong>Conformance levels for all standards/guide=
lines used to develop the product:
<ul>
<li><strong>Supports</strong>: The functionality of the product has at leas=
t one method that meets the criterion without known defects or meets with e=
quivalent facilitation.</li>
<li><strong><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"07bdbeba-76c8=
-4c04-9ebc-fe37801d9ab8">Supports with Exceptions</span></strong><span clas=
s=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"07bdbeba-76c8-4c04-9ebc-fe37801d9ab=
8">:</span> Some functionality of the product does not meet the criterion.<=
/li>
<li><strong>Does Not Support</strong>:<strong> </strong>The<strong> </stron=
g>majority of product functionality does not meet the criterion.</li>
<li><strong>Not Applicable</strong>:<strong> </strong>The criterion is not =
relevant to the product.</li>
<li><strong>Not Evaluated</strong>: The product has not been evaluated agai=
nst the criterion. &nbsp;This can only be used in WCAG 2.0 Level AAA.</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Conformance Tables&nbsp;</strong><br>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>WCAG</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>Table 1: Success Criteria, Level A</p></li>
<li><p>Table 2: Success Criteria, Level AA</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>2017 Section 508 Report</strong><br>
<ul>
<li><strong>Chapter 3: Functional Performance Criterial (FPC)&nbsp;=E2=80=
=93 Reports on user impact by disability type</strong><br>
<ul>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage without vision</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage with limited vision</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage without perception of colour</p><=
/li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage without hearing</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage with limited hearing</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage without vocal capability</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage with limited manipulation or stre=
ngth</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage with limited reach</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Minimize photosensitive seizure trigger=
s</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Usage with limited cognition</p></li>
<li><p class=3D"auto-cursor-target">Privacy<strong><strong><strong><strong>=
<strong><strong><strong><strong><strong><strong><br></strong></strong></str=
ong></strong></strong></strong></strong></strong></strong></strong></p></li=
>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Chapter 5: Software</strong></li>
<li><strong>Chapter 6: Support Documentation and Services</strong></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Legal Disclaimer</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;
<ul>
<li>"This report reflects the results of testing performed in 'XXXXX'&nbsp;=
with 'explanation of content selections used'. Some accessibility support f=
eatures are content dependent. As a result, some compliance exceptions note=
d in the VPAT arise from exceptions relevant to the content in the specific=
 title tested and do not reflect gaps in the "app name" application. Conten=
t accessibility may vary by title. This report is provided for information =
purposes only.'</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>As the cover page to the report, MHE authored&nbsp;VPAT Companion cover =
page that provides a 1-page overview of accessibility conformance report, i=
ncluding a Summary of Results.</p>
<h3 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-Whenshouldaproductrecei=
veaVPAT?">When should a product receive a VPAT?</h3>
<p>A VPAT is the final step in the auditing process. The report publicly de=
tails on the accessibility of an application's user experience, so it is im=
portant that your application is as compliant as you can make it before aut=
horing begins.&nbsp; In most circumstances, we suggest a remediation round =
between the audit and VPAT authoring to close as many outstanding gaps as p=
ossible.&nbsp; While no product is 100% accessible, we want to eliminate as=
 many "Does Not Support" and "Supports with Exceptions" criteria as possibl=
e.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>Because the VPAT should reflect customer experiences and not discrete ap=
plications, audits and VPATs may be scheduled by the DAIM team based on a c=
ombination of factors, including application readiness and common workflows=
.&nbsp;</p>
<h3 id=3D"VPAT/AccessibilityComplianceDocumentation-LifespanofaVPAT">Lifesp=
an of a VPAT</h3>
<p>A VPAT should be kept current and be revised&nbsp;every two years&nbsp;<=
em>at minimum&nbsp;</em>and updated periodically to document incremental im=
provements.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The TPM should maintain a the post-audit accessibility roadmap and prior=
itize backlog tickets that will increase documented conformance support.&nb=
sp; When new features are released, the TPM must work with the DAIM team to=
 ensure that accessibility updates are validated, so that VPAT updates can =
be made where appropriate.&nbsp;</p>
